    <methods>
      <methodStep>
        <description>
          <section>
            <title>Measure of thaw depth using metal thaw probe and organic layer depth by visual observation</title>
            <para>Thaw depth was measured using a metal thaw probe, which was inserted into the soil until there was resistance from frozen ground.  Thaw depth is reported as the distance from the moss surface to top of frozen ground.

Organic layer depth was measured by cutting into the soil with serrated knife and measuring the distance from the bottom of green moss layer to the organic-mineral boundary, as determined by visual observation.</para>
          </section>
        </description>
      </methodStep>
      <sampling>
        <studyExtent>
          <description>
            <para>Data were collected from Alaska permafrost borehole sites in July and August of 2015, September 2017, and August and September 2018.</para>
          </description>
        </studyExtent>
        <samplingDescription>
          <para>At each site, in 2015 we established three 20 meter long transects that were spaced 20 m apart and located adjacent to the permafrost boreholes. In 2017 and 2018 we sampled along a 50 meter or 100 meter transect at most sites, unless otherwise indicated.  Thaw depth was measured at 1 m intervals along the transect. Organic layer depths were measured at approximately 5 meter intervals.</para>
        </samplingDescription>
      </sampling>
    </methods>
